INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (8688,5,'2011-12-12 22:28:13','2011-12-13 03:28:13','What if you need to do more with less? In the past, that usually meant working longer hours and/or skimping on the quality, scope and completeness of work product. Today, I look at that challenge in a very different way.\n\nThe TopCoder Platform places a lens on top of your software factory, focusing in on key metrics within it\'s global marketplace. So, when I\'m trying to get more done within my budget the first thing I look at is the market and how my world looks within that market. What is my unit cost (cost per competition)? How long is it taking us to complete each unit and the subsequent project? What is our success/failure rate? Then, I make a couple adjustments and monitor the impact.\n\n<img style=\"vertical-align: middle;\" src=\"http://www.topcoder.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/Dashboard-Cost1.png\" alt=\"Unit Cost\" width=\"961\" height=\"269\" />\n\nHere is a quick example:\n\nIn December I have a budget of X. The amount of work I have planned requires us to produce Y units of output. My cost per unit in November was $3300 (average is $2800 for the past six months) so I knew that Y * $3300 could not exceed X (my budget). Based on the amount of work we need/want to get done in December, I knew that $3300 per unit would cause an overrun. There wasn\'t much I was comfortable cutting in terms of delaying or dropping features, which is what I would have traditionally done. Or, I would have asked for more budget and/or \"borrow\" from another group which would cause them to suffer.\n\nBut what if I could get my cost per unit down to $2600? Then I could still get everything on our roadmap done for the same budget. So, that is what we did. We tuned our approach to running competitions to lower the cost per unit. This, so far, has also had the side effect of increasing our success rate and lowering our time to produce each unit. A few of the adjustments we made were:\n\n1. Copilots updated the game plans for all projects in <a href=\"https://www.topcoder.com/direct/\" target=\"_blank\">Cockpit</a>. This gave us clear visibility for the full month, along with the projected costs and timelines.\n\n2. Encouraged our copilots to pay attention to the market. Identify areas of opportunity.  For example, if we\'re running high on assembly contest cost compared to the market, then figure out why and adjust accordingly. Also, schedule contests in an opportunistic fashion so we take advantage of positive market conditions. For example, if there are a lot of web design contests running today, but 30% less scheduled to be running 2 days from now then consider waiting a couple days to post your contest.\n\n3. Decompose further. If there are complex portions of a contest that are driving up the cost, then consider extracting the complex portion to a separate contest.\n\nI\'ll post more tips and tricks here in the coming months. If you have questions or specific topics you\'d like to hear about, please <a href=\"mailto:support@topcoder.com\" target=\"_blank\">let us know</a>.','Tuning Your Product Development','','publish','open','open','','tuning-your-product-development','','','2013-12-04 16:21:15','2013-12-04 21:21:15','',0,'http://www.topcoder.com/?p=8688',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (8715,5,'2011-12-22 15:38:40','2011-12-22 15:38:40','We\'ve been listening to your feedback and turned to the community to improve the user experience around viewing graphical submissions that come out of <a href=\"http://studio.topcoder.com\" target=\"_blank\">Studio </a>competitions like Web Design, Logos, Icons, Banners, etc. Take a look when you get a chance. In addition to having a much easier time viewing and comparing the many images within each submission, you\'ll notice quite a performance improvement.\n\n<img style=\"vertical-align: middle;\" title=\"Submission Viewer\" src=\"http://www.topcoder.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/new_submission_viewer1.png\" alt=\"Submission Viewer\" width=\"500\" height=\"588\" />\n\nNext on the roadmap for submission viewing is the ability to download all submissions at once and a friendly way to view wireframes within <a href=\"https://www.topcoder.com/direct/\" target=\"_blank\">Cockpit</a>.\n\nLet us know about any feedback or feature requests you have at <a href=\"mailto:support@topcoder.com\">support@topcoder.com</a>.\n\n&nbsp;','New Submission Viewer','','publish','open','open','','new-submission-viewer','','','2013-12-03 23:28:08','2013-12-04 04:28:08','',0,'http://www.topcoder.com/?p=8715',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (8770,5,'2012-01-09 17:09:43','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<div style=\"font-size: 12pt;font-family: arial;color: #000000;text-align: left\">\n<p style=\"color: #000000;margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em;line-height: 19px;font-size: 13px;background-color: #ffffff\" align=\"\"><span style=\"color: #2a4d7b\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: sans-serif\">How does a change agent drive necessary changes within a corporate environment that has adhered to sub-optimal</span><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"color: #000000\"></span></span><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: sans-serif\">operations?</span>\n</span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif\">\nThe researchers who developed Advanced Research Projects Agency Network (ARPANET) used the request-for-comments process to develop telecommunication network protocols. This hands-on use of the collaborative process is what gave birth to the Internet in 1969.\n</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial\">Intensely important leaps forward happen when people share ideas, processes and tools with others who have different and valued experiences and therefore, very likely a different solution to contribute. A corporate culture becomes bogged down by rigidity and lack of incentives. The daily work environment becomes affected by punishing results from opening up or sharing of ideas, tools or information. Things begins to erode. The foundation th</span><span style=\"font-size: 16px;font-family: Arial\">at was causing excitement and drive for development that founded the organization in the first place is destroyed.</span></p>\n<strong>On Point Read &amp; Presentation: <a href=\"http://info.topcoder.com/blog/bid/48923/Internal-Teams-Global-Communities-Making-it-Work-in-Open-Innovation-Crowdsourcing\">Internal Teams, Global Communities: Making it Work in Open Innovation &amp; Crowdsourcing</a></strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 20px\"><strong>Changing Cultural Course on the Open Seas </strong></span>\n\nYour corporate culture is a steam liner-sized ship which is actually a community of people.They\'re extremely difficult to turn around once charging ahead on the open oceans of the public domain - especially if currently profitable! The ship can\'t turn around until enough of the passengers are behind a new direction. Sometimes the need for a new direction gets ignored until the iceberg is actually visible.\n<p style=\"font-size: 16px;margin: 0px 0px 16px;padding: 0px;color: #383838;font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;line-height: 18px\" align=\"\">Places that have earned the high distinction of being great environments to work in usually followed the lead of an insider change agent. That person began to share information openly within the organization. A role was developed by the change agent who then applied energy to the role in a manner that brought about a natural process.This process usually unveils the 5 unique roles of a change agent.</p>\n1) The leaders of these organizations become aware that anything they say or do becomes a re-enforced action by managers. Much like a parent who is trying to hammer home a life lesson, <strong>change agents must stay on message</strong> and continually draw on real-world examples that resonate with their team. Remember, your kids repeat what you say!\n<p style=\"font-size: 16px;margin: 0px 0px 16px;padding: 0px;color: #383838;font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;line-height: 18px\" align=\"\">2) The mission, vision and stated values of the organization are upheld by everyone. Primarily by those in positions of leadership. <strong>Modeling is a very powerful tool.\n</strong>\n3) An extremely important point to remember is that human nature delivers its best when supported. In Open Innovation practices there are several key ways to continually support change. Most important of all is re-assuring those around you that some percentage of failure is accepted and expected, thus risk is supported. If you are changing something as big as adopting an Open Innovation or Crowdsourcing platform, those who are being asked to leverage the platform must understand that they have the proverbial green-light to experiment within the platform and a single failure will not make or break a program or determine someone\'s career path. <strong>Eliminate the fear of failure through consistent and clear messaging that experimentation is supported.</strong></p>\n4) When leadership walks-its-talk and vision and values drive performance, a culture of pride sets in. <strong>Change agents are consistent across all their activities</strong>. Even tangential ones that are not directly related to the change they are aspiring for. This adherence builds respect and actions are replicated when respect is earned.\n<p style=\"font-size: 16px;margin: 0px 0px 16px;padding: 0px;color: #383838;font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;line-height: 18px\" align=\"\">5) Create an exciting daily environment with true inspiration, authentically helpful incentives and genuine rewards that are worth putting a shoulder behind. Along with role #3, eliminating the fear of failure, <strong>a change agent must actively support experimentation and tinkering</strong>. Providing meaningful incentives while consistently supporting risk is a powerful combination that can help bring about the change you are seeking.</p>\n<p style=\"font-size: 16px;margin: 0px 0px 16px;padding: 0px;color: #383838;font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;line-height: 18px\" align=\"\">Deciding to embrace open innovation is a start. Shepherding the internal change that must take place to secure a sustained internal cultural movement is an entirely different beast that takes vision and applied consistency that is also flexible enough to alter incentives and communication of goals as the program moves from infancy to growth to sustained maturity.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;font-family: arial;font-size: 16px\" align=\"\"></p>\n\n</div>','Shepherding Open Innovation: 5 Roles of the Internal Change Agent','','draft','open','open','','','','','2012-01-09 17:09:43','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.topcoder.com/?p=8770',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (8773,5,'2012-01-09 17:16:15','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<div style=\"font-size: 12pt;font-family: arial;color: #000000;text-align: left\">\n<div align=\"left\" style=\"font-size: 12pt;font-family: arial;color: #000000\">\n<div style=\"font-size: 12pt;font-family: arial;color: #000000\">\n<div style=\"font-size: 12pt;font-family: arial;color: #000000\">\n<div style=\"font-size: 16px;font-family: arial;color: #000000\">\n<div style=\"font-size: 16px;font-family: arial;color: #000000\">\n<div style=\"font-size: 16px;font-family: arial;color: #000000\">\n<p align=\"\">Watching the thrashers at the local skateboard park doing Ollie&rsquo;s, flips, slides and grinds, it&rsquo;s easy to speculate how different this scene is from the vision of the person who first took a skate key out of a roller skate and bolted the separate halves to a one-by-six plank. &nbsp;He could never have foreseen Tony Hawk landing the 900.</p>\n<p align=\"\">We&rsquo;re not a world of avid readers of manuals. One person like that in any family or office is usually enough. To the eternal frustration of these people, the rest of us like to tinker, customize, modify and create.<br /><br />On Point Read: (link newest post Edison/Priestly)</p>\n<p align=\"\">The way people use cell phones actually changed our culture by imposing new expectations of social behavior and response. In the press and over the coffee table we hear about this often in the negative. There are too many operating systems, too many platforms, too many companies and too many devices that don&rsquo;t work with each other.&nbsp;&nbsp; </p>\n<p align=\"\">Much of this is the familiar error of perceiving the solution as a problem. Our technical environment demands a new skill set in business management, but the decentralization behind our innovative mobile apps open a whole new world of possibilities.</p>\n<p align=\"\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p align=\"\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px\"><b>The Silken Road</b></span></p>\n<p align=\"\">With the Amazon Silk operating system on <a href=\"http://reviews.cnet.com/tablets/amazon-kindle-fire/4505-3126_7-35022491.html\">the new Kindle Fire</a>, we see even the basic functioning of the portable device working across the communications network. The Silk OS breaks down functions into those that can be handled by the on-board hardware and more demanding talks that are done on Amazon&rsquo;s massive cloud-based resources.</p>\n<p align=\"\">The first-look skepticism about Amazon Silk was that it depends on a cloud resource over a communications link that may not always be available. This is like criticizing a horse because it relies on both its front end and hind end. Our ancestors found that people who ride horses are more mobile and productive, even if they have to get off and walk once in a while.</p>\n<p align=\"\">Silk does what any computer program does; it divides a job into manageable tasks and does them very quickly. Silk just applies that to the operating system as well.</p>\n<p align=\"\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p align=\"\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px\"><b>The Management Paradigm</b></span></p>\n<p align=\"\">That innovative orchestration of tasks is also the key for managing Crowdsourcing or Open Innovation projects. Like the Amazon Silk OS or cell phone apps, you break down the job into what you can do in-house and what can be done best by tapping outside talent. Then you bring in the outside resources in a way that fits your company&rsquo;s management flow.</p>\n<p align=\"\">Companies like TopCoder take that a step farther by hosting atomized development and design competitions that allow members of the Community to self-select which aspects of any given project they care to compete upon. By breaking the work down to its smallest components, companies gain the benefit of their work being accomplished by specialists who are sincerely qualified to deliver a strong output for the given atomized work. Because all aspects of work are completed via competition, clients receive multiple high-quality submissions <a href=\"http://info.topcoder.com/blog/bid/43505/6-Important-Ways-Crowdsourcing-is-Different-than-Outsourcing\">eliminating any single point of failure</a> in the development life-cycle. </p>\n<p align=\"\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p align=\"\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px\"><b>A Team of Mozarts</b></span></p>\n<p align=\"\">Japanese corporations formed partnerships in the 1980s intended to spread innovation across their industries. Companies quickly realized it was not in their best interests to send their top people to these committees because the other firms would benefit from their genius without giving as much in return. You assigned a Salieri to these committees, not a Mozart; a person who recognized genius but was not a valuable contributor.</p>\n<p align=\"\">Creating a Crowdsourcing resource that brings teams of workers together on projects for clients avoids the Salieri Effect. Done correctly, you get the best people working in the best environment toward the fastest solution.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>','How Competition in Mobile App Space is Driving Innovation Forward','','draft','open','open','','','','','2012-01-09 17:16:15','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.topcoder.com/?p=8773',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (8784,5,'2012-01-09 17:23:17','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Open with Optamologist analogy - #1 or #2 - until you eventually get the very best lens shape for your less than perfect eyes. Just like getting a new pair of glasses or contacts, in Crowdsourcing and Open Innovation you\'ve got to be looking through the lens, in this case a portfolio lens to not only see the entire scope of value, but more importantly, truly shift how your company approaches and accomplishes work.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nReference Jason Breed SMT piece on social innovation\n\nWhether Gigwalk (crowds microtasks) or TopCoder (competitive community &amp; open innovation - shared knowledge)\n\nProject by Project is the Wrong Lense - because individuals projects can and will fail - too much riding on one project, scuttle all momentum and doesn\'t change how you view things\n\nGet image of TopCoder fill rate (overall) - pie chart\n\nCreate image of Traditional vs. TopCoder\n\n- Traditional Fail 3 - 12 months, can be millions of dollars, nothing learned, can be down severly wrong path and it can simply be too late to make changes\n\nTopCoder -Failuere matter of weeks, no additional money spent, learn why particular contest didn\'t work, change it (specs, $$$) - re-try','Why You Need a Portfolio Lens in Open Innovation & Crowdsourcing','','draft','open','open','','','','','2012-01-09 17:23:17','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.topcoder.com/?p=8784',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (8786,5,'2012-01-09 17:25:41','0000-00-00 00:00:00','We all know the value of accessing virtual labor:\n\n1. Get to any shore - the value of geograhic cost differences, the value of diversity, without lock in to a specific lock in\n\n2. Lower over head\n\n3. Access to external talent - open inno, hyperspecialization\n\n&nbsp;\n\nBut what are the difficulties?\n\n&nbsp;\n\n1. Name that tune - In one of the hardest computer science classes my undergrad college offered (programming languages) one of the best students was sitting with a bewildered expression on his face. \"You look like you have a question.\" my professor asked. \"I do\", replied the student. \"OK - what is it?\"\n\n&nbsp;\n\n\"I don\'t know,\" the student replied. \"I\'m having trouble stating the question.\"\n\n&nbsp;\n\nWe don\'t always know what we want to ask and this can be a real challenge to tapping into virtual labor.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n2. Defining the Outcome - the problem here is the outcome we measure, may not be the outcome we want. At TopCoder we tend to refer to anything that is central to solving a project as a deliverable, and the things that get created along the way, but which are extraneous as artifacts. The other day I was on hold with a large bank to get some questions answered, when the associate helping me couldn\'t answer the question, I asked for his supervisor and he put me on hold. Then I was disconnected. I don\'t know if its the case here, but I have seen reports of call centers hanging up on customers to meet their SLAs. The outcome they are being managed on is the average length of call, or perhaps the number of long calls. This creates a perverse incentive - when the customer has a real hard problem (i.e. one they couldn\'t solve through the website) - they are likely to take a long time getting it solved, and the call center is likely the only way to get satisfaction. But the call center (at the employee and/or organization level) are incented to not help these customers - either by pushing them out with unsatisfactory resolutions or by just giviing up. Virtual labor is like this at a magnitude greater - how you define the solution space is part of how you define the problem. And you need to have a manner of resolution that enables both the provider and client to get good value.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n3. Keep it virtual means it\'s not just working from home\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThere is a tendency to get tied to a specific person. The problem is that person is not a permenant resource - they can take a job and leave the virtual labor pool, they can get sick, they can lose internet access. On software teams this is oftern called the \"hit by a bus\" test - could your team survive if any member was hit by a bus? (This problem is a big deal for employee/employer and contract/staffer relationships too, we just often over look it, because so and so is loyal and wouldn\'t leave, or maybe can\'t leave because of the economy, etc.)\n\n&nbsp;\n\nIn the virtual world it\'s easy and sometimes useful to personalize that virtual resource. It often starts innocently \"hey just send that file to my email.\" Then there is tasking by email favor \"can you do a couple more things.\" Then slueth payments \"I\'ll make sure you get $$$ for it.\" This way ends in ruin for everyone. Other competitors bailout on your project and eventually you lose your guy. That\'s not to say the virtual workforce should be completely impersonal, in fact at TopCoder we spend lots of time making sure we\'re community first and foremost. On the other hand we also strive for a highly disciplined process - so new competitors can on board themselves if and when they chose, and so that we can survive a virtual bus.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nIf you\'d like to find out how the TopCoder Community and Platform can help solve these problems for your organization.... CLICK HERE.','3 Challenges of Virtual Labor & Crowdsourcing','','draft','open','open','','','','','2012-01-09 17:25:41','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.topcoder.com/?p=8786',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (8788,5,'2012-01-09 17:30:53','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p>As a senior at UCONN (undergraduate), one of the classes I needed to take was of the Pass/Fail variety entitled <em><strong>Carribean Cultures</strong></em>. No offense to anyone from the Carribean, but I didn\'t care about it then, I can not recall ever using a specific piece of knowledge gained in that class to any advantage nor can I now recall any of the material or lessons taught. Of a very limited choice of classes to \"round out\" my education, this one seemed the most harmless, so I took it. Is that an inspiring tale of higher education?... Hardly.</p>\n<p>What if instead of a narrow grouping of classes from which I had to choose, there was&nbsp; a huge variety that allowed me to self-select courses that were outside my major? Would they be more valuable to me? Would they have potentially led me down new and deeper paths in my education and my career? Possibly and at this point impossible to say, but one thing is for certain, I wouldn\'t have chosen Carribean Cultures based on it seeming the easiest to record a \"P\" in.</p>\n<p>Many times it seems our educational system</p>\n<p>There is a trend happening in higher education and it might just be a movement. It is a realization that when individuals self-select the topics and subjects they truly care to get deeper immersed in, they do exactly that.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Big part of TopCoder = Self Selection - Karim, link back to B\'s article - what Self Selection means to our competitors. Talk about Google\'s 20% rule - link to article we write on that topic</p>\n<p>Why this works so wel in education - same principles apply - two shining examples</p>\n<p>Stanford\'s AI class</p>\n<p>Hillsdale class intro to the Constitution</p>','Why Self Selection Works in Education & Open Innovation','','draft','open','open','','','','','2012-01-09 17:30:53','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.topcoder.com/?p=8788',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (9033,5,'2012-01-10 18:29:49','2012-01-10 18:29:49','<p align=\"center\"><strong><em>Worlds Largest On-Demand Digital Community for Challenges and Competition Services Now Available Resource for All US Government Agencies</em></strong></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><strong><em></em></strong></p>\n<strong>Glastonbury, Conn., January 10, 2012</strong>  TopCoder, Inc., the leader in online programming competition, skills assessment and competitive software development, today announced the company has been awarded a contract under General Services Administration (GSA) Schedule 541 4G, Challenges and Competitions Services. Under the contract number GS-07F-0097Y, federal public sector organizations can access TopCoders best of breed innovation platform and 380,000+ member Community of digital creatives to address the collaboration and innovation needs and challenges of the United States Government by implementing new solutions that affect every aspect of Government processesfrom funding to acquisition, contracts, and reporting.\n\nThe appointment of TopCoder to a list of approved vendors is envisioned as part of a new Government-led emphasis to unify the efforts of multiple U.S. Agencies working to implement new distributed innovation acquisition models with the prime objectives of educating and evangelizing U.S. Government agencies on the power of open innovation, providing program implementation guidance to those agencies and showing measurable impact of the program success. The TopCoder platform and Community is now accessible to provide the same high level of software expertise to all federal agencies and departments that is being experienced by NASA and DARPA.\n\nThefederal government hasrepeatedly called for greater transparency and efficiency in the procurement ofproducts and services for all agencies. We believechallenges and competition services are a keyelement inshining a light onhow to engage the public in an open environment, said Rob Hughes, President and COO of TopCoder, Inc. This willprovide agenciesdirect access to solutions through output-driven contests and tournamentsusing TopCoders stringent and proven platform for promotion, evaluation and delivery.\n\nTopCoder, NASA and Harvard Business School have created a virtual platform environment in which government clients can use communities to conceptualize, build and manage real digital solutions and realize faster turnaround, higher quality and greater ROI. The groundbreaking TopCoder process adopts a highly \"adaptive\" approach to product development that allows continual evolvement through process in the entire software development life cycle.\n<h3><strong>Notable Successes</strong></h3>\nThe NASA Tournament Lab (NTL) program has already shown significant returns in its 24 month pilot trial including:\n\n- An optimization competition to develop a software algorithm to recommend the ideal components of a space medical kit for manned space missions. The ten day competition involved more than 400 participants and garnered nearly 6,000 code submissions. The winning solution performs kit optimization in 30 seconds compared to NASAs previous best known solution, a 360X performance improvement at a total cost of $25,000.\n\n- A planetary data ideation challenge to generate ideas for visualizations, analysis tools, educational applications and mash-ups from the agencys rich and deep Planetary Data System databases produced 35 unique idea submissions from 212 participants over the course of two weeks. NASA paid $3,250 for 5 valuable ideas with the winning concept just the outside of the box thinking that NASA was hoping to achieve.\n\n<strong>About TopCoder, Inc.</strong>\n\nTopCoder is the world\'s largest competitive software development community with more than 380,000 developers representing over 200 countries. The TopCoder community builds software for a wide-ranging client base through a competitive, rigorous, standards based methodology. This methodology results in a highly consistent set of software components allowing a software-as-parts approach to application development. For more information about sponsoring TopCoder events and utilizing TopCoder\'s software services and platforms, visit <a href=\"http://www.topcoder.com/\">www.topcoder.com</a>.\n<p align=\"center\"><em><strong>TopCoder is a registered trademark of TopCoder, Inc. in the United States and other countries. All other product and company names herein may be trademarks of their respective owners.</strong></em></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>###</strong></p>\n<em>Visit the <a title=\"NTL NASA Tournament Lab powered by TopCoder\" href=\"http://community.topcoder.com/ntl/\" target=\"_parent\">NASA Tournament Lab</a> (NTL) for more details on current and past challenges.</em>','TopCoder Awarded General Services Administration (GSA) Schedule Status','','publish','open','open','','topcoder-awarded-general-services-administration-gsa-schedule-status','','','2012-01-10 18:29:49','2012-01-10 18:29:49','',0,'http://www.topcoder.com/?p=9033',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (9103,5,'2012-01-24 12:07:55','2012-01-24 12:07:55','<br /><strong>MBA Students Can Build New Businesses Entirely On Internet From Idea through Product Roll Out</strong>\n\nGLASTONBURY, Conn., Jan. 23, 2012 /PRNewswire via COMTEX/ -- TopCoder, Inc., the leader in online programming competition, skills assessment, and competitive software development, announced today that it is working with faculty members at Harvard Business School ( www.hbs.edu ) to provide an environment where HBS MBA students can build new online businesses, from idea generation through product development and final roll out to market. In support of the School\'s new FIELD course (Field Immersion Experiences for Leadership Development), part of the required first-year MBA Program curriculum, TopCoder has created an online platform, a virtual \"factory\" environment, in which student entrepreneurs will explore how to use professional communities and digital creatives to conceptualize, build, manage, and grow real digital products and businesses. See http://community.topcoder.com/hbs-field/ for full details.\n\n\n\"We want our students - tomorrow\'s business leaders - to become comfortable managing and building products in a rapidly evolving world,\" noted Alan D. MacCormack, one of ten faculty members at HBS responsible for the launch and design of FIELD. \"The resources, immediacy, cost savings, and overall improvements in quality and process provided by the Internet are dramatically changing how organizations work at the most fundamental level. Business formation, product development, sales, and marketing are all undergoing fundamental shifts. We see working with the TopCoder Community as a way to help our students understand this new reality.\"\n\nThe TopCoder Community was challenged to create a dedicated HBS portal within which student projects will run starting as early as this month. The platforms created by the TopCoder Community will be an integral part of the third module of HBS\'s FIELD course, which challenges more than 900 students - working in teams of six - to develop and launch a microbusiness in an accelerated time frame. Competitions began January 9th for prototype themes and wireframes with full builds of mobile and web storyboards, logo designs and mobile/web assembly starting February 15th.\n\n\"We are providing the practical foundation for a new age of competition in the fastest growing market in the world - the always on, always changing world of online business,\" said Jack Hughes, Co-Founder and Chairman of TopCoder, Inc. \"We believe this program can be a model to help fuel entrepreneurship and the spirit of business competition by breaking down the entry barriers in terms of access to talent and overall cost.\"\n\nAbout TopCoder, Inc.\n\nTopCoder is the world\'s largest competitive software development community with more than 380,000 developers representing over 200 countries. The TopCoder community builds software for a wide-ranging client base through a competitive, rigorous, standards based methodology. This methodology results in a highly consistent set of software components allowing a software-as-parts approach to application development. For more information about sponsoring TopCoder events and utilizing TopCoder\'s software services and platforms, visit www.topcoder.com .\n\nTopCoder is a registered trademark of TopCoder, Inc. in the United States and other countries. All other product and company names herein may be trademarks of their respective owners.\n\nAvailable Topic Expert(s): For information on the listed expert(s), click appropriate link.Jack HughesProfNet - http://www.profnetconnect.com/jack_hughes\n\nSOURCE TopCoder, Inc.\n\nCopyright (C) 2012 PR Newswire. All rights reserved','Harvard Business School and TopCoder Community Fuel Entrepreneurship with Groundbreaking Online Innovation Platform','','publish','open','open','','harvard-business-school-and-topcoder-community-fuel-entrepreneurship-with-groundbreaking-online-innovation-platform','','','2012-01-24 12:07:55','2012-01-24 12:07:55','',0,'http://www.topcoder.com/?p=9103',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (9163,5,'2012-02-03 16:07:00','2012-02-03 16:07:00','<p>TopCoder works with large enterprise corporations, government agencies, and innovative tech companies.</p>\n<p><strong>Here\'s a few recent highlights from our customers.</strong></p>\n<table border=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><img src=\"http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5027/5836247702_4029e4ddd0_m.jpg\" alt=\"Alcatel Lucent Logo\" width=\"124\" height=\"55\" /></td>\n<td valign=\"top\">\n<h3>Alcatel Lucent Community powered by TopCoder</h3>\n<p>- After creating the look and feel for the <a href=\"http://community.topcoder.com/alcatel/\">Alcatel-Lucent Community</a> site, our TopCoder members created <a href=\"http://www.alcatel-lucent.com/wps/portal/newsreleases/detail?LMSG_CABINET=Docs_and_Resource_Ctr&amp;LMSG_CONTENT_FILE=News_Releases_2010/News_Article_002300.xml&amp;lu_lang_code=en\">100 new Web 2.0 applications</a> in 100 days on top of a set of open APIs. Apps featuring new geo-location, travel, social and consumer purchasing capabilities emerged from this innovation challenge.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"height: 65px;\" border=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/facebook_logo.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-7871\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/facebook_logo.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"124\" height=\"55\" /></a></td>\n<td valign=\"top\">\n<h3>Sponsorship -</h3>\n<p>As Facebook continues to grow, access to the best innovators and developers in the world\'s largest development community delivers true value to their organization. Branded on-site participation at the <a href=\"http://community.topcoder.com/tco11/\">TopCoder Open</a> provides their team unsurpassed insight into our top community performers.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"height: 65px;\" border=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><a href=\"http://www.topcoder.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Lending-Tree-Logo-124x55.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-7878\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Lending-Tree-Logo-124x55.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"124\" height=\"55\" /></a></td>\n<td valign=\"top\">\n<h3>Virtual Software Factory -</h3>\n<p>Lendingtree has engaged our community for full developmental life-cycle capabilities spanning conceptualization, wireframe creation, storyboards, prototypes and product development and testing, while creating new websites featuring intuitive user experiences that convert more customers.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"height: 65px;\" border=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><a href=\"http://www.topcoder.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/NSA_PrintLogo.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-7873\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/NSA_PrintLogo.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"124\" height=\"55\" /></a></td>\n<td valign=\"top\">\n<h3>Tournament-Patron -</h3>\n<p>The National Security Agency has been an avid and engaged <a href=\"http://community.topcoder.com/tco11/\">TopCoder Open</a> patron since 2005. The ability to directly connect with top tier programmers allows the NSA to educate our best on the truly important work the Agency performs on a daily basis.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"height: 65px;\" border=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><a href=\"http://www.topcoder.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Yandex.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-7874\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Yandex.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"124\" height=\"55\" /></a></td>\n<td valign=\"top\">\n<h3>Sponsorship -</h3>\n<p>Yandex, the largest search engine in Russia, sponsored the TopCoder Open 2010 in order to gain access and become part of the TopCoder community.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"height: 65px;\" border=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><a href=\"http://www.topcoder.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/youdao-web-logo.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-7876\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/youdao-web-logo.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"124\" height=\"55\" /></a></td>\n<td valign=\"top\">\n<h3>Private Label Sponsor</h3>\n<p>- The desire to identify top-talent in a specific geo-locality prompted Youdao, a Chinese based search engine, to host a multi-stage programming challenge drawing in over 17,000 active participants. TopCoder\'s ability to create the infrastructure, usher in an engaged community and provide Youdao with detailed performance metrics drove value throughout the engagement.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"height: 65px;\" border=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-6381\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/ppx-logo.png\" alt=\"PayPal X Logo\" width=\"124\" height=\"55\" /></td>\n<td valign=\"top\">\n<h3>PayPal X Contests powered by TopCoder</h3>\n<p>- PayPal\'s new set of APIs offer developers unlimited possibilities to easily monetize their ideas by providing connectivity in a secure manner to the world\'s financial systems. The TopCoder Community was called upon to innovate on top of the new APIs with a focus on functionality across a broad spectrum of platforms and devices.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n','Case Studies','','trash','open','closed','','case-studies','','','2013-12-10 22:36:29','2013-12-11 03:36:29','',0,'http://www.topcoder.com/?page_id=9163',0,'page','',0);
