INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (13144,10,'2013-12-12 11:05:51','2013-12-12 16:05:51','<p><a href=\"http://www.topcoder.com/iss\" /><img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/NTL_ISS.jpg\" width=\"100%\" /></a></p>\n\n<p>DNA sequencing has revolutionized biological research and is set to transform medicine as well as this technology scales. Machines like Ion Torrents Proton sequencer will deliver a $1000 genome in a day. One of the keys to processing genetic data economically is compressing and decompressing the data with high efficiency, resulting in small file sizes and short processing times. TopCoder members were challenged to make the data storage as efficient as possible in both time and space.\n</p>\n\n<h4>SOLUTION</h4>\n\n<p>After achieving successful results in an initial algorithmic-based pilot project run on the TopCoder platform, NASA, in cooperation with Harvard Business School and TopCoder, launched the NASA Tournament Lab (NTL). The NTL empowers NASA to order up solutions on demand through Open Innovation competitions. The TopCoder platform provides NASA with flexible and secure means to launch and manage a wide variety of initiatives. The participation of TopCoder Community members in these various competitions helps NASA source innovative and breakthrough solutions. This repeatable process delivers extreme value outcomes in a consistent, cost effective and innovative manner.</p>\n\n<h4>HIGHLIGHTS</h4>\n\n<p>-- Built an open-sourced, Bluetooth enabled, Android based, 12 Lead ECG application that can be utilized on the International Space Station as well as in various 3rd world environments.</p>\n<p>-- Helped the Planetary Data System (PDS) publicize and create value from their massive cache of highly technical, astronomic data. Various contests ran in succession to first make the technical data accessible to a much wider audience, followed by contests to build functionality around this data that was then exposed via an Open API allowing the general public, teachers and students to craft iOS and Android applications, bringing the project full-circle.</p>\n<p>-- Created a detection algorithm to spot the presence of wheeled vehicles in proximity to a pipeline with the ability to distinguish between a security threat &#8211; an un-authorized vehicle &#8211; and a non-threat such as wild-life or a downed tree limb.</p>\n<p>-- Building in part on the experience with NTL, NASA has opened the new Center of Excellence for collaborative Innovation. CoECI extends the reach of NASAs innovation program to any Federal agency, such as HHS/CMS, providing them access to the TopCoder Community and Open Innovation Platform.</p>','NASA','','inherit','closed','closed','','13142-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-12 11:05:51','2013-12-12 16:05:51','',13142,'http://209.202.141.147/13142-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (13145,10,'2013-12-12 02:05:49','2013-12-12 07:05:49','<p><a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/megablast.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/megablast.png\" width=\"100%\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cutting-edge computational work is consistently under-resourced. To counteract this challenge, it traditionally requires deep pockets or access to talented coders and algorithmists who are willing to spend an exorbitant amount of time on the project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Harvard Medical School was facing this exact challenge for a complex DNA sequencing alignment challenge. This was a real-world problem, where the limitations of existing tools severely constrained the ability to pioneer new advances in medical knowledge.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>SOLUTION</h4>\r\n<p>Harvard Medical School enlisted TopCoder to help find a faster, more accurate solution for a tool that calculates the edit distance between a query DNA string and the original DNA string. This is critical for making high-precision, high-throughput readouts of the immune system. Prior to the TopCoder contest, the best known solution, MegaBLAST, processed 100,000 sequences to a high degree of accuracy, yet required 2,000 seconds to execute. A full-time, Harvard resource that spent a year on this unique problem was able to produce an improved outcome, reducing the computational time to 400 seconds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With $6,000 in total prize money, 733 registrants and 122 members submitting working algorithms, TopCoder provided HMS with a winning solution that performed hundreds of times faster and at a higher degree of accuracy, reducing the time to execution to just over 16 seconds.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>HIGHLIGHTS</h4>\r\n<p>-- Harvard Medical School enlisted TopCoder to help find a faster, more accurate solution for a tool that calculates the edit distance between a query DNA string and the original DNA string. This is critical for making high-precision, high-throughput readouts of the immune system. Prior to the TopCoder contest, the best known solution, MegaBLAST, processed 100,000 sequences to a high degree of accuracy, yet required 2,000 seconds to execute.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-- A full-time, Harvard resource that spent a year on this unique problem was able to produce an improved outcome, reducing the computational time to 400 seconds. With $6,000 in total prize money, 733 registrants and 122 members submitting working algorithms, TopCoder provided HMS with a winning solution that performed hundreds of times faster and at a higher degree of accuracy, reducing the time to execution to just over 16 seconds.</p>','Harvard','','publish','closed','closed','','harvard','','','2013-12-12 13:13:55','2013-12-12 18:13:55','',0,'http://209.202.141.147/?post_type=case-studies&#038;p=13145',0,'case-studies','',0);
